## Code Owners Guidelines

### Team Structure

- **@maintainer1, @maintainer2**: Project maintainers with global oversight
- **@core-team**: Core development team responsible for main functionality
- **@api-team**: Backend API development team
- **@ui-team**: Frontend UI/UX team
- **@frontend-lead**: Frontend team lead
- **@backend-lead**: Backend team lead
- **@devops-team**: DevOps and infrastructure team
- **@test-team**: Quality assurance and testing team
- **@docs-team**: Documentation team
- **@security-team**: Security team
- **@database-team**: Database administration team
- **@mobile-team**: Mobile development team
- **@mobile-lead**: Mobile team lead
- **@platform-team**: Platform-specific development team
- **@integrations-team**: Third-party integrations team
- **@plugins-team**: Plugin development team
- **@performance-team**: Performance optimization team
- **@i18n-team**: Internationalization team
- **@senior-developer1, @senior-developer2**: Senior developers with expertise in specific areas

### Rules and Guidelines

1. **File Patterns**: Use glob patterns to match files and directories
2. **Order Matters**: More specific patterns should come after general ones
3. **Multiple Owners**: Use spaces to separate multiple owners
4. **Team vs Individual**: Use team handles for broader coverage, individual handles for specific expertise
5. **Fallback**: Always have a fallback owner for critical files

### Best Practices

- **Critical Files**: Always assign maintainers to critical configuration files
- **Security Files**: Assign security team to security-related files
- **Documentation**: Assign docs team to documentation files
- **Tests**: Assign test team to test files
- **Build Files**: Assign devops team to build and deployment files

### Adding New Owners

When adding new owners:

1. **Update Teams**: Add new team members to appropriate teams
2. **Update Patterns**: Add new file patterns as needed
3. **Review Assignments**: Ensure all files have appropriate owners
4. **Test Changes**: Verify that CODEOWNERS file syntax is correct

### Emergency Override

In emergency situations, maintainers can override CODEOWNERS by:

1. **Direct Merge**: Merging PRs without waiting for reviews
2. **Hotfix Process**: Using emergency hotfix procedures
3. **Temporary Assignment**: Temporarily assigning different reviewers

### Monitoring and Maintenance

- **Regular Review**: Review CODEOWNERS file quarterly
- **Team Changes**: Update when team members change
- **File Structure**: Update when project structure changes
- **Performance**: Monitor review times and adjust assignments

### Troubleshooting

Common issues and solutions:

- **Syntax Errors**: Check GitHub's CODEOWNERS syntax documentation
- **Missing Reviews**: Ensure owners have proper permissions
- **Too Many Reviews**: Consolidate owners for frequently changed files
- **No Reviews**: Add fallback owners for all file patterns

### Resources

- [GitHub CODEOWNERS Documentation](https://docs.github.com/en/repositories/managing-your-repositorys-settings-and-features/customizing-your-repository/about-code-owners)
- [CODEOWNERS Best Practices](https://docs.github.com/en/repositories/managing-your-repositorys-settings-and-features/customizing-your-repository/about-code-owners#codeowners-file-location)
- [Glob Pattern Reference](https://git-scm.com/docs/gitignore#_pattern_format)
